==English==
===Etymology===
Late Latin ''[[#Latin|parenthesis]]'', from Greek ''[[παρένθεσις]]'', from ''[[παρεντιθεναι]]'' ‘place in beside’, from ''[[para-]]'' + ''[[en-]]'' + ''[[τιθέναι]]'' ‘to place’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/pəˈrɛnθəsɪs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|parenthes|es}}

# A clause, phrase or word inserted (usually for explanation or amplification) into a passage which is already grammatically complete, and usually marked off with brackets, commas or dashes.
# (''Rhetoric'') A [[digression]]; the use of such digressions.
# Either of a pair of brackets, especially round brackets, '''[[(]]''' and '''[[)]]''', used to enclose parenthetical material in a text.
# (''Maths, Logic'') Such brackets as used to clarify expressions by grouping those terms affected by a common operator, or to enclose the [[component]]s of a [[vector]] or the [[element]]s of a [[matrix]].

====Synonyms====
*[[bracket]]
*[[round bracket]]

